Date: Mon, 18 Sep 2000 10:45:18 -0400
From: Marianne Hopp <mhopp@iri.ldgo.columbia.edu>
Source: WHO outbreak report, 18 Sep 2000
<http://www.who.int/disease-outbreak-news/n2000/september/18sept2000.html>

Rift Valley fever in Saudi Arabia
As of 17 Sep 2000, the Health Ministry of Saudi Arabia reported 16 deaths
in humans, 14 males and 2 females, from Rift Valley fever in the Jizan
region in southwestern Saudi Arabia. Laboratory confirmation of the disease
was made by the WHO Collaborating Centre at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta, Georgia, United States. A total of 38 suspected
cases has been reported. No additional cases have been reported in the past
two days.
The Health Ministry is implementing control measures, including the rapid
disposal of dead animals and intensive application of insecticides to
eradicate mosquitoes and larvae. Health education messages about handling
sick and dead animals and ways to avoid being bitten by mosquitoes are also
being disseminated to the population in the affected region.
The Yemen Ministry of Health sent a team to the area bordering Saudi Arabia
to intensify surveillance for human and animal disease. No suspect cases
have been reported in Yemen.
Prior to this report, Rift Valley fever has been confined to the African
continent.
For more information, please see the WHO Fact Sheet on Rift Valley fever.
*******
[02
Date: Mon, 18 Sep 2000 08:08:11 +0300
From: Dr. Shamsudeen Fagbo, DVM <oloungbo@zajil.net>
Source: Arab News - 18 Sept 2000 (edited)

All schools and colleges in Jizan have been closed indefinitely as a
precautionary measure to prevent the spread of a potentially fatal viral
disease identified as Rift Valley fever which has hit the region over the
past week, killing 18 people and affecting 32 others.
However, Health Minister Osama Shubokshi, who was in Jizan which borders
Yemen to supervise preventive measures, declared Saturday that the
situation in Jizan was satisfactory and there was nothing to worry about.
"Don't worry, the situation is under control. We have identified the
virus." the minister told reporters after inspecting hospitals in the
region. He said he was visiting the region following orders from the higher
authorities.
"As the number of victims increased, the Jizan governorate has decided to
close all schools, institutes and colleges in the region until further
notice," Al-Madinah Arabic newspaper reported. But Shubokshi said the
schools were closed to spray insecticides and clean the premises.
Medical experts believe the virus came to the region through sheep imported
from Africa. A large number of sheep have died in Jizan following infection
with the disease. The outbreak was first reported in Al-Ardah town where
victims have suffered high fever, diarrhea, and bleeding. In some cases,
the disease has developed into kidney and liver failures, causing death. An
official source at the ministry said it was the first time that Rift Valley
fever had appeared in the Kingdom.
He said the virus was transmitted to humans from animals either through
direct contact or by mosquitoes. Health officials said there was an
effective vaccine against the disease for animals.
--
Dr. Shamsudeen Fagbo, DVM
Jeddah,Saudi Arabia
<oloungbo@zajil.net>
