[3
Date: Mon, 18 Sep 2000 15:32 EST
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters Online 13:08 EST [edited
Story Filed: Monday, 18 Sep 2000 1:08 PM EST

Saudis Ban Some Livestock Imports to Fight Disease
--------------------------------------------------
Saudi Arabia said Monday it was banning the import of livestock from
several African and Arab countries to fight the Rift Valley Fever, a
disease which has killed at least 16 people in the kingdom.
A Health Ministry official told the official Saudi Press Agency that the
ministry had rushed experts to the affected region in southwest Saudi
Arabia where they were spraying mosquito-infested areas, getting rid of
dead livestock and controlling the movement of other livestock.
Measures also included a temporary ban on the import of sheep, goats and
camels from countries including Somalia, Djibouti, Eritrea, Kenya,
Ethiopia, Sudan and Yemen where the official said similar cases had been
reported in the past.
Saudi Arabia Sunday said at least 16 people died and another 38 were being
treated in hospitals following the outbreak of the disease in Jizan area,
near the Yemeni border.
Rift Valley Fever, a hemorrhagic disease, is spread from livestock to
humans by mosquitoes or by contact with infected animals.
Saudi newspapers had earlier reported up to 30 deaths in Jizan from a
mysterious disease.
Neighboring Gulf Arab states, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates, said
Monday they had not been affected by the disease. Qatar said it was not
planning to stop the import of livestock from Saudi Arabia.
--
