[The first report is the WHO official confirmation of Rift Valley fever
outside of Africa. This report gives a case fatality rate of 42 percent,
much higher than expected, suggesting a significant underreporting of the
milder cases.
In the second report, the press mentions that schools were being closed due
to the epidemic, but the Ministry of Health official clarified the closures
as being done to permit the spraying with insecticides. It should be
emphasized that disease transmission is primarily through bites of infected
mosquitoes and from handling uncooked meat of infected animals and NOT
through person-to-person contact.
The banning of animals from Somalia, Djibouti, Eritrea, Kenya, Ethiopia,
Sudan and Yemen seems to be based on prior reports of RVF in Somalia and
Kenya. In 1997-1998 there was a major epidemic of RVF in Somalia and
Kenya. To date there have not be reports of RVF in Djibouti, Eritrea,
Ethiopia, Sudan and Yemen, but given the proximity to other areas of known
prior transmission in areas with less than complete reporting this may be
the justification behind the decision. - Mod.MPP
